  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2 id="dial-in-workflow">Dial-in workflow for cleaner pour-over cups</h2>
      <p>Even an excellent grinder needs the right dial-in routine. Most bad grinder complaints in pour over come from unstable workflow: old beans, random dose sizes, inconsistent pouring, or changing multiple variables at once. If you want faster consistency, keep your workflow boring and systematic.</p>

      <HeroSteps
        title="Pour-Over Dial-In Rhythm"
        subtitle="Use a repeatable 3-step cadence so grinder changes actually make sense"
        steps={[
          { label: 'Baseline', icon: 'target', actions: ['Pick one coffee and dripper', 'Fix dose and brew ratio', 'Brew three cups unchanged'], time: '~15 min total' },
          { label: 'Adjust', icon: 'list', actions: ['Change one click at a time', 'Log drawdown and flavor note', 'Avoid multi-variable changes'], time: '~5 min per brew' },
          { label: 'Maintain', icon: 'calendar', actions: ['Brush burr chamber weekly', 'Deep-clean monthly', 'Keep separate settings by roast'], time: '~10 min monthly' },
        ]}
        outcome="Cleaner cups, fewer random drawdowns, and faster recipe confidence"
      />

      <h3>Use one baseline recipe before comparing grinders</h3>
      <p>Start with a simple recipe and keep it fixed for at least three brews: one coffee, one dripper, one filter type, one water profile, one brew ratio. For example, use 20 g coffee to 320 g water and a total brew time target around 2:45 to 3:15 for a medium roast. Once that is stable, compare grinders or settings. If you change coffee, temperature, and grind at the same time, you cannot tell what caused the result.</p>
      <p>If you are still dialing in brew ratios, bookmark our <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a>. It is easier to diagnose grinder settings when your ratio and dose are already predictable.</p>

      <h3>How to adjust grind size without chasing your tail</h3>
      <p>Use one-direction adjustments with small steps. If coffee tastes sour, thin, and underdeveloped, move one click finer and brew again. If it tastes bitter, drying, and heavy with slow drawdown, move one click coarser. Resist the urge to jump five clicks based on one cup. Small changes reveal pattern; huge changes hide it.</p>
      <p>A practical trick is to log only three things for each brew: grind setting, total drawdown time, and one flavor note. After five brews, patterns become obvious. You do not need a complex spreadsheet. A phone note is enough. This habit matters more than having a grinder with 200 settings.</p>

      <h3>Reduce fines and sludge with process, not just hardware</h3>
      <p>Better grinders reduce fines, but process still matters. If cups are muddy, first check your pour technique and agitation. Aggressive swirling, long bloom stirring, and high turbulence can push extra fines into the filter bed and stall flow. Use gentler pours and keep agitation consistent.</p>
      <p>Second, clean your grinder burr chamber regularly. Old residue breaks off as micro-particles and can mimic poor grinder performance. A quick brush every few brews and monthly deep clean often fixes random bitterness issues that people blame on beans.</p>
      <p>Third, be realistic with roast level. Very dark coffee can produce more sediment feel and bitterness at settings that work well for light-to-medium roasts. If you switch roast profiles often, expect to keep separate baseline settings.</p>

      <h3>Who should skip this guide</h3>
      <p>Skip this roundup if you only drink pre-ground coffee and do not plan to adjust grind size, because these recommendations are for people brewing whole beans and tuning recipes. Also skip if your primary goal is espresso-only dialing. In that case, you will get better results from a dedicated espresso-focused grinder guide instead of a pour-over-first list.</p>
      <p>If your setup is mostly automatic drip with no intent to change brew variables, your money may go further by upgrading filters and water quality first. This guide is for readers who want to improve cup clarity and repeatability by choosing a better grinder and using it intentionally.</p>

      <h3>Electric vs manual: choose for your real morning constraints</h3>
      <p>Manual grinders are excellent if you brew one cup and enjoy a slower routine. They also travel better and often deliver strong grind quality per dollar. But if you brew for two people before work, manual effort can become the bottleneck that pushes you toward rushed technique and inconsistent cups.</p>
      <p>Electric grinders are less romantic but easier to repeat. If consistency is your top priority, workflow simplicity usually beats theoretical burr advantages. A slightly less perfect burr set with stable daily routine often produces better coffee than a premium grinder used inconsistently.</p>

      <h3>When to upgrade from your current grinder</h3>
      <p>If your current grinder gives acceptable flavor and predictable drawdowns, you may gain more by improving water, filters, or pouring consistency first. Upgrade when you repeatedly hit these issues despite good process:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Drawdown times swing wildly with the same recipe.</li>
        <li>Cups taste astringent and muddy even after coarsening.</li>
        <li>Retention and static cleanup add enough friction that you skip fresh grinding.</li>
        <li>You need one grinder to support multiple methods and your current model cannot keep up.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If your main target is high clarity for V60, moving to a stronger filter-focused grinder can be a meaningful jump. If your goal is flexibility across espresso and filter, a crossover grinder may be the smarter upgrade path.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 id="flat-vs-conical">Flat burr vs conical burr for pour over</h2>
      <p>For pour over, the flat-versus-conical debate is less about right and wrong and more about flavor shape plus workflow preference. Flat burr grinders often produce cups that feel cleaner and more separated, where citrus, floral, and tea-like notes are easier to identify. Conical burr grinders often emphasize sweetness, heavier body, and a rounder profile that can feel forgiving with medium and darker roasts. Neither profile is universally better. It depends on what you enjoy in the cup and how much adjustment effort you want to put in each week.</p>
      <p>If you mainly brew light roasts and want to highlight clarity in V60-style brews, a strong flat burr option like Ode Gen 2 usually feels rewarding. If you brew a mix of roast levels, value easier all-around behavior, and want flexibility across methods, conical models like Encore ESP or Opus can be the better daily fit. Manual conical grinders can also deliver excellent cup quality with very low retention, especially if you only brew one or two cups at a time.</p>
      <p>In practice, your process consistency will influence results as much as burr shape. Stable dose, predictable pouring, and regular cleaning can make a conical grinder outperform a poorly managed flat burr setup. If you are deciding between the two, choose the grinder that supports your routine. A grinder you use consistently will produce better coffee than a grinder with perfect specs that you avoid because workflow feels annoying.</p>
